			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>minivasn wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Personally I hope that players will not be able to create click-links on the fly.  Right now the creation of clicklinks is limited.  If it becomes easily doable I think we'll start seeing people use it for griefing.  Meaning
<br />

<br />
&lt;a href = "charref://50000/1111111/&amp;quot;Test&amp;quot;"/quit"&gt;&amp;quot;Click here for something funny!&amp;quot;&lt;/a&gt;
<br />

<br />
Click the link and you just might get dropped off-line.  Actually probably cannot for a charref, but if you can create a clicklink with script, macro, or manual entry someone will use it to grief people.
<br />

<br />
If you can enter an itemref manually (or Script, or Macro) into chat you'll have people attempt to scam others with fake refs.  Again, you can accomplish it more easily, because the information isn't hard to figure out.  Being easier just brings the idiots out to play.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />

<br />
or worse:
<br />

<br />
"&lt;a href = "charref://50000/1111111/&amp;quot;Test&amp;quot;"/petition haha I've been exploiting for over 2 years now and i occationally try to pick up minors ingame, you mofo's what you gonna do about it eh? ban me? hahha loosers...\n /s I like to have sex with children, any 10-12 year olds here? give me a /tell, thanks. ( PS: this is a serious request, don't bother giving me a tell if you're not infor some hot steem action)."&gt;&amp;quot;Click here for something funny!&amp;quot;&lt;/a&gt; "
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Personally id rather more see them keep the binary format, or keep the blobdata to $args[2] (its own separate packet untriggarble from chatline) and just have both accept HTML-tags to make it easier to directly load in or show html-contents in a window.
<br />
But separating chat and blobdata regardless of binary or not i think is important to security, to prevent creation on the fly, and to more easily separate logging / tracking of what's sent over the socket or not in case of abuse.
<br />

<br />
Either way, easy or not, with a bot someone can easily do the same, i had to install yes/no confirmations in my bot on admin-commands that are crucial and then timers so it doesnt accept a confirming "yes" if its sent too early, that way malign multi-line/multi-command clicklink triggers from a window wont do any harm to a bot since a multitrigger clicklink sends all the commands at once, thus 2nd+ command ex a confirming "yes" will always be sent too early from a multitrigger clicklink (#L "test" "/tell bot something\n /tell bot something new \n /tell bot something more"), but still alot of bot-types out there having admin-level crucial commands that reacts no a command directly, thus if someone know who the admin is, and who their bot is, and know their bot-type be it custom or not, they can easily send a trigger that makes he admin perhaps add the sender as a member, or a co-admin etc.
<br />

<br />
IMO all clicklinks from windows should have a popup warning or a "tips" mouse-over that shows the contents of the clicklink when hoovering above it, that would be the best solution, since then people would know what they clicked before doing so and it's really not that hard to build a mouse-over yellow-tip into the AO client.
<br />

<br />
Amona</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
